rth of Revelation compares Protestant, Catholic, and Jewish reflections on revelation from 1750 to 1850 and asserts that a strategic transformation in the term’s meaning secured its relevance for the modern age. Tuska Benes argues that "propositional" revelation, understood as the infallible dispensation of doctrine, gave way to revelation as a subjective process of inner transformation or the historical disclosure of divine being in the world. By comparatively approaching the unconventional ways in which Protestantism, Catholicism, and Judaism have rehabilitated the concept of revelation, The Rebirth of Revelation restores theology to a central place in modern European intellectual history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aReasonxHistoryy18th century. 0aReasonxHistoryy19th century. 0aRevelationxHistory of doctrinesy18th century. 0aRevelationxHistory of doctrinesy19th century. 0aTheologyzGermanyxHistoryy18th century. 0aTheologyzGermanyxHistoryy19th century. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aCatholicism.  aJudaism.  aProtestantism.  acomparative religion.  acrisis of historicism.  ahistory of theology.  anatural history.  anineteenth-century Germany.  aphilosophy of religion.  areason.  arevelation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754309940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487543099423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487543099/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK